1
00:00:00,170 --> 00:00:04,400
In this video we are going to learn Gateway routing pattern.

2
00:00:04,850 --> 00:00:11,810
Gateway routing pattern is wrote request to multiple microservices with exposing a single endpoint.

3
00:00:12,740 --> 00:00:19,610
This pattern is useful when we want to expose multiple services on a single endpoint, and route them

4
00:00:19,610 --> 00:00:23,210
to the internal back end microservices based on the request.

5
00:00:24,730 --> 00:00:28,120
When the client needs to consume several microservices.

6
00:00:28,120 --> 00:00:34,540
Gateway routing pattern offers to create a new endpoint that handles the request and route these requests

7
00:00:34,540 --> 00:00:35,890
for each services.

8
00:00:36,670 --> 00:00:42,280
For example, you can think an e-commerce application might provide services like customer shopping

9
00:00:42,280 --> 00:00:44,140
cart, discount, and order history.

10
00:00:44,170 --> 00:00:46,180
You can see the image on the slide.

11
00:00:46,210 --> 00:00:52,390
The gateway routing pattern is exposing one single endpoint to the client application when the client

12
00:00:52,390 --> 00:00:53,530
hit this endpoint.

13
00:00:53,560 --> 00:00:59,200
The routing pattern routes to the request several internal microservices which including the customer

14
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:01,060
shopping cart, discount and order.

15
00:01:01,540 --> 00:01:08,320
So that means the gateway routing pattern is useful if you have such a case, like a client is consuming

16
00:01:08,320 --> 00:01:09,880
multiple microservices.

17
00:01:11,290 --> 00:01:17,230
If one of the microservices are changed or replaced with other microservices, the client doesn't know

18
00:01:17,230 --> 00:01:20,140
anything and not need to change any code.

19
00:01:20,170 --> 00:01:26,320
On client side, it can continue to continue to making requests to the gateway, and the only change

20
00:01:26,320 --> 00:01:28,960
will be the configuration of the routing changes.

21
00:01:30,580 --> 00:01:37,390
By this way, API gateway abstracts your backend microservices from the client applications with allowing

22
00:01:37,390 --> 00:01:39,910
you to keep client codes simple.

23
00:01:39,910 --> 00:01:43,660
Even back end services are changed on behalf of the API gateway.

24
00:01:45,130 --> 00:01:51,430
Also, this pattern can be very useful when you have multiple API versions of the same microservices.

25
00:01:51,460 --> 00:01:58,780
That means if you deploy our microservices APIs with Bluegreen or Canary deployments, you can gradually

26
00:01:58,780 --> 00:02:03,250
shift your requests to new API with using the gateway routing pattern.

27
00:02:04,150 --> 00:02:09,070
Gateway routing pattern gives you the flexibility to use different API versions.

28
00:02:09,070 --> 00:02:10,630
Routing to the request.

29
00:02:10,660 --> 00:02:17,710
If the new version of API has got exceptions, it can be quickly reverted back to making only a configuration

30
00:02:17,710 --> 00:02:19,360
change at the API gateway.

